11.1 Introduction

We previously introduced three performance metrics when analysing a control system, namely
  1. transient response,
  2. stability, and
  3. steady-state error.
We have now discussed closed-loop stability in detail as part of Chapter 9, which allowed us to quantify the level of stability when visualising the frequency response of loop transfer function in a relevant diagram. In Chapter 10 we considered steady-state error specifications, as well as the associated type of loop transfer behaviour required to achieve the particular steady-state specification. While this assures the correct behaviour as time tends to infinity (), or equivalently, when frequency tends to zero (), it does not consider the transient behavior of the output response. Chapter 11 will focus on deriving design specifications related to transient performance that can be interpreted in the frequency domain. These frequency-domain design specifications will form the basis of the feedback control design that we will use in Chapter 12.

11.2.2 Relationship with stability margin

Recall that the stability margin, , is defined as the distance between the critical point and the closest point of when visualised in a Nyquist diagram, as shown in Figure 11.2.
Figure 11.2: Graphical representation of stability margin in arithmetic complex plane.
Mathematically, this can be written as
,
Which implies that the distance between any point on and the critical point is always equal to or greater than . The stability margin is related to the gain and phase margins in that it gives us an indication of closed-loop stability based on how far away is from the critical point. If we divide both sides of the equation above by , we get
,
where the left-hand side of the above equation is now the magnitude response of the sensitivity function, and the right-hand side is the inverse of the stability margin. Making the sensitivity function small at all frequencies will therefore ensure that the stability margin is large based on the relationship above. This means that our objectives to track reference signals and have good stability margins are aligned — both require small sensitivity functions. However, for the purposes of a good stability margin, we only need to make small when in the vicinity of the critical point.
The mathematical relationship above also implies that the maximum value of will be equal to , namely
,
which we can read off from a Bode magnitude response graph of in order to design for or analyse the stability margin.

11.2.3 Sensitivity M circles in the complex plane

The previous section has shown that there is a relationship between circles originating at the critical point and the magnitude response of the sensitivity. Following from this, if we want to determine if the magnitude response of the sensitivity function is ever equal to some value M, namely
,
then we can draw a circle centred on the critical point, with radius , and if intersects this circle, then will have a magnitude response of M at the frequency corresponding to the intersection. However, if never intersects the circle, then never has a magnitude response of M.
The code below generates sensitivity M circles for .
clear
 
M_array=[0.5 1 2];
the = (0:1:360)*pi/180;
 
figure, hold on
for M=M_array
circ = -1+1/M*exp(1i*the);
plot(real(circ),imag(circ),'-',lineWidth=2)
end
plot(-1,0,'ro',MarkerFaceColor='r')
text(-1,-.1,'-1','Color','r')
xline(0,'-'),yline(0,'-')
legend('M=0.5','M=1','M=2')
axis equal

The code block below generates the resulting grid lines in the log-polar plot for a range of M values.
clear
M_array=[0.1 0.3 0.5 .7 1 2];
 
figure, hold on
for M=M_array

grid on
 
What we should first notice is that M circles in the complex plane map to warped boundaries in the log-polar plane. We can still imagine them as "closed shapes", where the resulting grid lines that span the entire phase range close off entire regions below them. We also see that as the M values increase, the boundaried regions shrink and approach the critical point (represented with a red dot), as was the case with the M circles in the complex plane. When grid lines corresponding to the magnitude response of are overlaid in the log-polar plane, we refer to this type of plot as an inverse Nichols chart.
Assuming we can generate these grid lines in the log-polar plane, we can then make assertions about the magnitude response of when the response of is also present in the log-polar plane.

Example

The locus is shown to intersect the grid line (matching our previous assessment), which means that the sensitivity function will have a magnitude response that exceeds for frequencies that place within the contour. 11.3.1 Design objective

As the name implies, the sensitivity function and complementary sensitivity functions are related by
,
where the complementary sensitivity function is defined as

Recall, with reference to the block diagram in Figure 11.3, that the output response is related to all exogenous signals by
where the complementary sensitivity function describes the mapping from reference and noise to the output .
Figure 11.3: Block diagram of closed-loop system with exogenous signals.
As previously discussed, we would like to make for the low-frequency range where we expect to act, as this will give us good reference tracking for sufficiently low-frequency reference signals. We then want to make for the high-frequency range where we expect high-frequency noise term to act, in order to avoid noise making its way to the output of our system. An idealised Bode magnitude response of the complementary sensitivity function is shown in Figure 11.4.
Figure 11.4: Idealised Bode magnitude response of complementary sensitivity function.
Given that we only have agency over the structure of , we therefore want to adjust in order to shape the behaviour of as required. In order to do this, we need to be able to define design specifications on that relate directly to design specifications on . With this in place, we can then adjust using , based on the design requirements of , such as bandwidth, overshoot, and steady-state error.

When displaying the grid lines of the complementary sensitivity magnitude response on a log-polar plot, we refer to this as a Nichols chart.

11.4 Closed-loop design specifications

We have now developed a means of determining the magnitude response of or based on visualisation of in a log-polar plot. The next step is to understand how to convert user specifications into design specifications on the closed-loop system. If we can place design constraints on or , we can then convert it to design constraints on , as before.

11.4.1 Degree of closed-loop systems

While we do not yet possess the tools to manipulate in a sensible way, we will eventually do so in order to shape or . An important thing to be aware of is that the order of will dictate the order of and . If the loop transfer function is given by

So the order of , which is the denominator polynomial of and , will always be less than or equal to the order of , depending on whether there are cancellations in . This means that if we know what order will take, we can then expect equivalent order from and .

11.4.2 User specifications

User specifications are often given as high-level closed-loop objectives. This can include various system parameters that we have already considered, such as:
  1. steady-state error
  2. maximum percentage overshoot
  3. peak time
  4. settling time
  5. gain margin and phase
  6. stability margin
  7. closed-loop bandwidth
Specifications (5)-(7) are easy to determine in the frequency domain and have already been covered in some detail, whereas (2)-(4) are time-domain specifications that must be suitably represented in the frequency domain. Specification (1) is also a time-domain specification, but we have already shown that we can interpret steady-state error in the frequency domain by consulting the low-frequency behaviour of .

11.4.6 Tracking bounds in the log-polar plane

Once and have been determined, we can then represent these constraints in the log-polar plane. We do this because we then have a clear relationship between , which we will be able shape via , whilst also being able to assess the adherence to the closed-loop specifications.

As previously mentioned, we consider all frequencies for , whereas we only consider frequencies up to the desired closed-loop bandwidth frequency, , for . In other words, must not enter the region enclosed by the blue dotted line for any frequencies, and simultaneously, must stay outside the region enclosed by the green solid line for frequencies . It is important to emphasize that these simplified tracking boundaries does not guarantee that the original time-domain specifications will be adhered to. As such, it is good practice to check the behaviour of the relevant output response (e.g. step response) to ensure that our interpretation in the frequency domain matches that of the time-domain.

Example

Using the log-polar plane, determine whether , when placed in a unity-feedback loop, will satisfy the closed-loop second-order specifications of a settling time of 5 seconds, percentage overshoot of 25%, zero steady-state error for reference step inputs.
is Type-1, so we can be certain that we can achieve zero steady-state error for reference step signals, as the position error constant is
.
The other specifications match the previous examples, so we have already determined , , and as
,
rad/s.
The code below generates the design boundaries in the log-polar plane and also plots the frequency response locus of . Frequency point is also highlighted on the locus, as we require all frequencies up to to be outside (effectively above) the enclosed green region.
clear
s = tf('s');
 
L = 5/s/(s+2);
 
w0 = 1.13; %closed-loop bandwidth frequency
Ma = 1.35
Ma = 1.3500
Mb = 0.5;
 
 
figure, hold on
 
M = [Ma Mb];
for k = 1:2
phi = linspace(0,2*pi,1e4);
c = -1;
r = 1/M(k);
K = c + r*exp(1i*phi);
 
mag_K = 20*log10( abs(K) );
phi_K = angle( K )*180/pi;
for i=1:length(phi_K)
if( phi_K(i) > 0), phi_K(i) = phi_K(i)-360; end
end
 
if( k==1 )
plot( phi_K(2:end-1),-mag_K(2:end-1),'--b',LineWidth=2 )
else
plot( phi_K(2:end-1),-mag_K(2:end-1),'-g',LineWidth=2 )
Lw = squeeze( freqresp(L,w0) );
 
plot(angle(Lw)*180/pi,20*log10(abs(Lw)),'go',MarkerFaceColor='g',MarkerEdgeColor='k')
end
end
[magL,phiL] = nichols(L,{1e-3,1e3});
plot(squeeze(phiL),squeeze(20*log10(magL)))
 
plot(-180,0,'ro',MarkerFaceColor='r')
legend('$|T(j\omega)|\leq M_A$','$|T(j\omega)|\geq M_B$','Interpreter','latex')
xlim([-360,0]),ylim([-50,50])
Using the desired , , and values shows that does adhere to the design constraints, which means that we have potentially met the original time-domain specifications of a settling time of 5 seconds and percentage overshoot of 25%. We can verify this using a step response, as generated from the code below.
T = feedback(L,1);
figure, hold on
step(T,6)
yline(1.25,'--b','$\% OS=25\%$','Interpreter','latex')
xline(5,'--r','$t_s=5$s','Interpreter','latex','LabelVerticalAlignment','bottom')
ylim([0 1.4])
The step response shows that both the settling time and overshoot specifications have been met.
It is easy to show that if we instead considered , then we would not meet the design constraints in the log-polar plane, as well as the original time-domain constraints. A comparison of and is shown using the code below.
clear
s = tf('s');
 
L1 = 5/s/(s+2);
L2 = 10/s/(s+2);
 
w0 = 1.13; %closed-loop bandwidth frequency
Ma = 1.35; %overbound
Mb = 1/sqrt(2);
 
 
figure, hold on
 
M = [Ma Mb];
for k = 1:2
phi = linspace(0,2*pi,1e4);
c = -1;
r = 1/M(k);
K = c + r*exp(1i*phi);
 
mag_K = 20*log10( abs(K) );
phi_K = angle( K )*180/pi;
for i=1:length(phi_K)
if( phi_K(i) > 0), phi_K(i) = phi_K(i)-360; end
end
 
if( k==1 )
plot( phi_K(2:end-1),-mag_K(2:end-1),'--b',LineWidth=2 )
else
plot( phi_K(2:end-1),-mag_K(2:end-1),'-g',LineWidth=2 )
Lw1 = squeeze( freqresp(L1,w0) );
Lw2 = squeeze( freqresp(L2,w0) );
 
plot(angle(Lw1)*180/pi,20*log10(abs(Lw1)),'go',MarkerFaceColor='g',MarkerEdgeColor='k')
plot(angle(Lw2)*180/pi,20*log10(abs(Lw2)),'go',MarkerFaceColor='g',MarkerEdgeColor='k')
end
end
[magL1,phiL1] = nichols(L1,{1e-3,1e3});
plot(squeeze(phiL1),squeeze(20*log10(magL1)))
[magL2,phiL2] = nichols(L2,{1e-3,1e3});
plot(squeeze(phiL2),squeeze(20*log10(magL2)))
 
plot(-180,0,'ro',MarkerFaceColor='r')
legend('$|T(j\omega)|\leq M_A$','$|T(j\omega)|\geq M_B$','Interpreter','latex')
xlim([-360,0]),ylim([-50,50])
%
T1 = feedback(L1,1);
T2 = feedback(L2,1);
figure, hold on
step(T1,6),step(T2,6)
yline(1.25,'--b','$\% OS=25\%$','Interpreter','latex')
xline(5,'--r','$t_s=5$s','Interpreter','latex','LabelVerticalAlignment','bottom')
ylim([0 1.4])
As shown in the log-polar plot and step response, violates the percentage overshoot boundary.
